<user_name>L R< /user_name>< Text>
I contacted the company to have my motorcycle towed from Oakland to San Leandro.   I explained to the dispatcher that the motorcycle had been damaged because I was involved in an accident,  and the front fender is smashed into the front tire and pushing would be difficult.

I was told the driver would meet me in 45 minutes.  After 1 hour I called for an update, the dispatcher advised it would be 20 minutes.  Fast forward to 2.5 hours later,  the driver called and said he was outside.   I walked outside, no tow truck or driver.  I  called him back, he was given the wrong address.

Finally, he arrived with a flatbed tow truck but didn't not have a motorcycle dolly (fender is pushed into the front tire).  A friend at work had to assist with moving the motorcycle (I couldn't because I was injured from the accident).

The Road King is finally secured and ready to go.     We arrived at the location and needed assistance from a stranger to down load and push the motorcycle.

The driver was apologetic and professional,  but the overall service sucked.   I want to mention that the truck was not from the company I called and it was out of Union City.  I picked this company because they stated they were located in Oakland.< /Text>

<name>William Arthur<//name><time>1595480149115< /time><userid>109102500037810049253< /userid><Rating>1<//Rating>< review>
DO NOT CALL THIS TOWING SERVICE. They will rob you.

My car broke down close to my apartment in a PG&E work area requiring me to tow my vehicle prior to 7am the following day. I scheduled a tow truck driver from a different service to tow my car at 6:30am. The tow truck driver ended up arriving 30 minutes late but within that time frame I called Rocket Towing to schedule a tow truck from their service to tow my vehicle as I was worried that the initial tow truck (from a different service) wasn't going to show up.
However, shortly after I scheduled Rocket Towing to come out to my car, the initial tow truck driver messaged me that he was still coming. I called Rocket Towing back, literally 13 minutes from when I first called them (saved a picture of it on my phone), and they told me I needed to pay a $50 cancellation fee.
It had not even been 15 minutes, and they were telling me I needed to pay $50 to cancel which, by the way, they NEVER told me about $50 cancellation fees during the initial phone call to Rocket Towing. Otherwise, I would not have booked it or at the very least, I would have cancelled the other tow truck driver.
On top of that, the tow truck driver who I had initially called, said that towing service actually gives him jobs and that it is common practice among tow truck drivers to not charge if a person calls and cancels in less than 15 minutes from the booking.

THIS PLACE WILL ROB YOU. DO NOT CALL THEM.  Rocket Towing, how can you people live with yourselves taking $50 dollars from someone who needs help, struggling to fix their car, in the middle of a recession??? Shame on you.< /review>

All 6 of us found something to suit our fancy. We hung out here with friends visiting from out of town for several hours, and that seemed acceptable and even the norm for this place. <Text>Dropped in for an early morning coffee and breakfast bite with my son. First, ambience is terrible - bad acoustics so voices result in a deafening racket. Coffee is passable but there are only two meal choices - bagel/cream cheese/lettuce/tomato or biscuit/egg. More importantly - no substitutes! I was not allowed to have a bagel and egg. I was told that the egg was in exact proportion to the muffin - I said I didn't care, put the egg on the side. Please try again. A conference was held in a back room whereupon the waitress returned and announced still no substitute! Later, an older woman appeared from the back with my egg and muffin - no explanation, no apology. IMHO a first class miserable bi-ch!
20 minutes after ordering, and going to the counter to retrieve my coffee, still no orange juice. 10 minutes after that, I went back to the counter and asked for my juice "OMG, I forgot" replied the waitress. Still, she proceeded to work on new customer orders. Again I went to the counter - "I'd like my orange juice now, please!" At which point, she reached for a plastic cup, swooped up a plastic jug of juice from under the counter and poured me a glass - it took 10 seconds (and hopefully didn't have her spit in it).
So, miserable inattentive service and an owner who doesn't give a sh-t. Avoid if you're looking for a decent breakfast.< /Text>< pictures>

< Text>
Coin operated car wash that only takes tokens. You will can either use cash or card. You can trade in tokens if you don't use all of them. It will cost at least 4 dollars to get your car covered in soap and rinsed off. The soap in the brush it very thick and takes a little work to get off your car. I would suggest it to anyone who wants to save a few bucks on a car wash. If you want to spend a few more dollars you can go to one of the drive through car washes. As you can see in the photo there are multiple stalls. Sometimes it is packed so don't always expect to get a stall right away.</Text>

110549196135027047246</UserId.>
< name>
misstrwbrylvr< /name>
< Time>
1539656709386< /Time>
<Rate>5<//Rate>< Text>
1 check-in
Yess! I've been waiting for the SF location to open since the beginning of the year, it's been such a long suspenseful wait! I was hoping I would be the first customer and first reviewer haha.

I have always loved the quality of the Palo Alto location and believe that their milk tea is the closest to Taiwan's in the bay area. The boba is also the closest you can get here in the bay, it doesn't melt in your mouth like it does in Taiwan, but it's still honey sweet and chewy.

This location is good, but not as good as the Palo Alto location because the tea taste isn't as strong. However, I'm still rating it 5 stars because this is the best boba milk tea in the city after growing up here and seeing the quality of boba go downhill over the years.

And yes, boba guys don't come even close, it's definitely overrated and not authentic.
Gongcha is more authentic because they have a creamy taste in their milk tea similar to Taiwan's.

If you can't instantaneously travel to Taiwan but have a crazy craving for boba, definitely come here!< /Text>

< Review>
About 7 months ago I called about a VW Passat I found on their website. I forgot who I spoke to but they were extremely kind and explained everything perfectly. She offered to put my application in for the car over the phone since I lived two hours away. She called me back within hours to tell me that I qualified and to tell me what my APR and monthly payments would be.

I went into the dealer and everyone I encountered had amazing customer service. The woman that assisted me was the wife of the owner. The Owner was very friendly. It is a family owned business and everyone gets along very well. They make you feel like part of the family.

It has been 7 months and I have had no problems with the car at all. The only minor issue I noticed is that all my tired are different brands but all in good condition. The car has been amazing. The customer service was amazing as well.

They made everything as easy as possible for me.

My car came with a spare tire, all the tools required and a tire lock. It was very organized.

My boyfriend bought a VW Passat from a different dealer before I bought mine and his came with no tools, no tire lock, and a poor spare tire. He also paid more for an older model with more miles.

I got a great deal for the year and model of the vehicle I bought. I would highly recommend buying a car from them!< /Review>

<time>1545106148876</time><user_name>Ken Counts<//user_name>< Pictures>
[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMTcZxQt-Fmr3fwHav36pIIXnytvfM-02SvDQ9y=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPFiMIvoWVM27OMN2tb0aXXgdDnaOVuTaOLHRd6=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//Pictures>
<UserId.>108603218996237213901<//UserId.>< Text>
Well, bravo. You guys got me on a technicality, and apparently a number of other customers as well.

If you're looking at buying from Abramovich make sure you THOROUGHLY read and understand ALL of the documents they have you sign and initial.  They love to tout the "clean carfax"... which is technically true at the time you buy the car.  Even if they know something just hasn't made it on the Carfax report yet.

If you're like me and don't pay close enough attention to the "Statement of Facts" under sub-section "G" you might not realize you're signing away on "structural damage per auction announcement".  A few months or years later you'll check the Carfax again and see the structural damage on there. But not on the "clean" Carfax Abramovich gives you. Sometimes it takes awhile for the damage to update on Carfax.

My personal opinion? Abramovich knows this and likes to work in the gray area, but.... i can't prove it. So what do I know?

Shame on me for letting that one slip by. I didn't want to believe it was true, but there was my signature. Unfortunately, I'm not the only one who's been awe struck at, what appears to be, such a great deal on a car.  Check out other Yelp, Google, and BBB reviewers on this place, and you'll see other customers who fell for it too.

Just make sure you read those forms closely and understand what you're signing.<//Text>

<name>Jennifer H</name>< review>
Be very careful buying your car from this place! Yes, their cars are very clean, but that's about it. I saw a Hyundai Sonata advertised on autotrader, I was informed that it was previously a rental vehicle, but was also told that the car is up to date and everything has been done and in good condition.

There was imperfections on the body of the car. Nicks, dents and scratches here and there. Stains on the seats.. Nothing major, but since I was paying in full, I figured I could get a better deal due to those issues. The younger guy who was initially helping me, constantly kept telling me the dents and nicks were unnoticeable, and that at night, you wouldn't even see it. He also said it's so minor that I won't need to fix it. I thought to myself, am I buying the car or are you buying it? Is it your money or mine? I also informed him that there was a more prestine Sonata we saw a few days prior for a better deal, but someone else bought it before we could. He kept questioning me, arguing with me and even spent time on his phone checking autotrader ads! Makes me wonder, they know what they can give the car to me for, what's the point of standing there, checking the competitors, wasting everyone's time. Either we're going to do this deal or not. That's all I wanted. I didn't want to go back and forth. I told them I was paying cash. In addition, I had just gotten off a 9 hr shift and took a two hour drive in traffic from San Diego.

So after dealing with the little guy, the big brother comes to save him from his terrible sales technique. He gave me the closest price, I agreed and closed the sale.

As he was driving home, about 20 miles in, he noticed a rotating, rocking type sound coming from the back wheels at around 60-70 mph. He informed me of it, but I told him he was probably listening a little too hard. So I decided to drive it. Initially everything sounded good for about 10 miles. I started noticing it and the car also felt like it was rocking.

2 days after having the car, the tire pressure light came on for the rear left tire, where the noise was coming from. Fast forward to 4 days after. We took it to the dealership and found out the alignment is off, so it caused the car to rock, which made the two back wheels wear from the inside out. The dealership also informed us that the air filters has never been changed. Estimated repairs will cost about $500.

We called yevi to inform him of it. We tried being polite, but he began arguing with us saying that it was normal wear and tear on the tires and that we just need to change it. We emphasized that he told us the car was in good condition. He just kept defending himself and arguing, saying this is "normal wear and tear". It wasn't getting anywhere. I understand the usual wear on tires, but this car is at 38k miles, and the type of rocking was not "normal". The type of wear on the tires was not "normal". Yet, the man kept arguing. So finally at the end he tells us to drive the car BACK to Murrieta and he will replace the tires. SERIOUSLY? That's the best you can do and you own a dealership? Is that how you resolve issues? I guess now we have to fork out $200 for repairs and find the time to drive all the way back out there, wasting time and money. Ill probably just save my time and energy and deal with this myself, rather than going back to deal with them again. Way to go guys!!!! I will be reporting to the BBB.

Note: They will trick you by putting a paper on the dashboard of each car with it checked as "warranty OR as-is". However, all vehicles have it checked for "warranty" but when they have you sign the papers, they may have you sign for as-is no warranty (the same paper, but this time they will switch it to 'as-is') and will explain that the car is still under manufacturer warranty and that the original dealership will take care of any issues, not them. Very misleading. So keep an eye on that. Additionally, they didn't wash my car after I made the purchase. I should listened to my gut feelings.

BE CAREFUL! DON'T FALL FOR THE PRETTY CARS AND YELP REVIEWS.</review>

<review>My wife and I had an amazing experience with Abramovich Motors.  We have never purchased a car online and were skeptical.  We live in Kansas City and Abramovich Motors is in California.  After deciding on a 2013 BMW X6 we went to our local bank and had all of the financing done.  Yevi, the owner, sent all of the paperwork overnight to me and I took it to the bank.  Yevi and my bank collaborated from there and completed the transaction.  Yevi shipped our car from California and we had it in 4 days.  Yevi also went above and beyond for us.  After we received the car we notices a couple of really small scratches on the hood and Yevi purchased the repair touch up paint and sent that to us.  Yevi also notice we had a low tire when he shipped the car.  He told me to take it to our BMW dealership and have the tire replace and that he would reimburse me.  The cost of the tire with labor was $479.48.  I sent Yevi the receipt and he mailed me a check within a week.  Abramovich Motors is solid online dealer with a high level of integrity and amazing low prices on their vehicles.  I hope Abramovich motors is still in business when I need my next vehicle.  Thank you Yevi for the fantastic experience!

TJ & Tammy Carley<//review><pictures>None<//pictures><user_name>TJ Carley< /user_name><Rating>5</Rating>< Response>

<Time>1613053913419<//Time><rate>4</rate><Text>Its not surprising that the word "fun" can be found in the word funnel cake because everytime I had fun there was a funnel cake there. Normally, to find a funnel cake you either¬†have to go to a¬† fair,¬† a¬† sporting event, or an amusement park. But now, you can get one of these delicious deserts anytime you want.
Located on the corner of 6th and Vineyard in Ontario, is Fairgroundz a modest size sweet shop that sells everything that will make your eyes pop and make your mouth water. If Willy Wonka had a second factory, this would be it. They sell everything from scoops of icecream, to shaved ice, to cookies. But their specialty is the funnel cake, made fresh and cooked to order. The one I had was called the Banana Cream Pie and it was amazing.
Lastly,  this past year was a year unlike any other, a year that none of us will ever forget. It has been like a dark cloud over all of us, but having that funnel cake was like having the sun touch my skin. It was a nice reminder that there was still good/fun things in the world.
Check out Fairgroundz in Ontario.< /Text>< pics>

< Review>
This is a tiny home in the wall sorry of place. We were craving relief from the heat and stopped in for a snow cone. It was nice that they had a couple of sugar free options but the ice was much coarser than I expected it to be. They also serve ice cream, funnel cakes, and a couple of other deep fried goodies. But the servers, while friendly, were rather slow and they didn't seem to be excited it energetic... Since the theme of the place is food from the fair I was expecting a certain amount of happiness and fun... Probably won't be going back but if you have a craving, you should check it out.<//Review>

< Text>
Aside from being greeted by a bearded host who refused to wear a mask (it was hanging from his ear) it was a good experience. But this almost made us turn around at the door. Bartenders were also preparing drinks maskless. Makes one wonder about what's going on in the kitchen. Spacing between tables was way too close. On top of one another.  It's my opinion, restaurants not following these basic safety rules, during this period (brand new all time high in US cases today! 80K) should be immediately closed. While it would be a shame, so would a dinner becoming a super spreading event, leading to multiple illnesses and death.

Having said that. Our waitress was lovely, attentive, and always near.  Her recommendation of the Blood Orange Martini was terrific. The fried calamari is pretty close to perfect. Fresh, crispy, but just a light batter.

Fried Chicken entree ($28) is as good as it gets in a restaurant like this, out here in Palm Springs. The Pork Chop ($42) was moist and not dried out. Served with a nice salad.

Fix the mask issues and this place is a winner.<//Text>

<userid>101741871043887400347<//userid>< review>
While on our first trip to Palm Springs, a place well known for its overwhelming amount of culinary options... we chose The Tropicale, which was recommended to us. We‚Äôre so glad we did! The dining room is beautiful in all its 1970s feel. The food was RIDICULOUS!

My son (this place is child friendly, though there aren‚Äôt kids menus) had the prosciutto and Brie pizza and it was GLORIOUS!  My wife had the burger which had Brie, caramelized onions and truffle mayo which she loved. I had their boneless fried chicken which I wouldn‚Äôt normally get but it was one of their specialties, and I SO glad I did! It was KILLER! We ended up spending a bit more than we would have liked, but this is the type of meal where you leave feeling like you stretched every penny despite the cost with no regret. Totally worth it.

The staff is super friendly too. Our waiter was great, but the busing team was fantastic too! They were like an army, always coming by, but never too much... they seemed to anticipate every tine they were needed to bring refills, take plates away or what have you. They were great.

I would make this a must on your next Palm Springs trip!<//review>

< Review>
Great food and service but only giving 2 stars for those two things. Their COVID-19 precautions are basically non existent. Servers are wearing masks and there‚Äôs hand sanitizer at the front but that‚Äôs about it. The tables are way to close to one another (as I‚Äôm posting this, I‚Äôve noticed other reviews also mentioned this). There was a party of 30+ people sitting next to our 2 seater table. They were drunk and having a good time but none of them were wearing mask and only about half of them were sitting in their seats at any given time. When not in their seats, they were filling the isles between all the surrounding tables, including ours. Other tables who also had the unfortunate luck of being seated next to them also looked uncomfortable with the situation.

It‚Äôs disappointing that Tropicale is still booking reservations this large in the middle of a pandemic in a county that has so many positive cases.

I am writing this 3 days after I went and Riverside county has now shut down indoor dining. That party could‚Äôve been a super spreader event happening right before of us.

I hope Tropicale actually reads this and reconsiders their approach to a safe dining experience in the midst of a pandemic.</Review>

< Text>
Step back in time to the mid-century modern era. Fantastic vibe with a lot going on. I had the largest and prettiest white sangria I have ever seen. We were a party of two and decided to do small plates. The Pu Pu platter was outstanding. The satay, beef skewers and ribs were exquisitely tender and seasoned perfectly. The shrimp were crispy and delucious. I personally didn't like the spring roll as I found the wrapper gelatinous and would have preferred a crunchy one. The Goat cheese and beet salad was excellent but it would have been better had the beets been roasted. The avocado goat cheese and tomato flatbread was also delicious but we had to take most of it home because the food was so plentiful. Would highly recommend going here.</Text>

<Rate>3</Rate>< user>
101939008472418654893<//user>
<Name>Delaney Dreckman</Name><Time>1557177833629< /Time>< text>
We ate here with a group of 7. Our waitress was really nice, we had a reservation and the host sat us immediately at an outdoor table. I appreciated the fans & misters, but the two sitting closest to the misters were visibly wet the entire meal. Especially the person sitting by the palm trees, the water was actually accumulating on the palm tree & soaking directly into her hair. We asked the waitress to turn the misters off, she said it would get too hot and they were all on one system instead of individual systems. It was around 80 degrees, so we would have been fine with just fans & not the misters, but it wasn't an option. Later in the evening, we asked a manager to turn off 1 fan which he happily did. So still wet, but not blowing air on us (by now it was dark and the fans weren't needed).

We got the large drink to share with the group, that was festive & super fun. Everyone liked their food and our waitress was very funny & the service was very quick.

I'm sure if we sat at any other table in the restaurant, I would have given 5 stars.< /text>

< username>
James Wan<//username>
<date>1569503096339< /date><Pics>None</Pics><gmap_id>0x80db1bbb4e3ab7fd:0xa279cb4f4e6b940c< /gmap_id>< Response>

<userid>102595820736418415381<//userid>< rate>
1</rate>
< review>
With so many five star reviews to this place you might think "The Tropicale" is a Michelin rated restaurant?

We'll ... This Dade County reminiscent gin joint is far from it, but they try really hard in more ways than two.

Their service is in your face attentive and cheery from the eye candy in the front to the wait staff buzzing around. Weekend nights are simply a happening place to be here too.

The menu here is quite long and a bit over the top. It matches the decor quite apropos in a non sparingly manner too. The pizza is made heavy with lots of dough and lots of cheese. The Poopoo platter seems like a good value, but the chicken and beef skewers are tougher than Management's response to customer concerns and comments.

The only thing going for the many visits from folks are the drinks. The alcohol really flows strong in this joint. Cocktails are large and with big personalities. I can certainly imagine folks here writing their reviews immediately after getting hammered.

If you're looking for value or a near Michelin star meal, you will have to look elsewhere. If what you seek is a happening time, with some people watching and a stiff drink - The Tropicale is your place. Just don't confuse the line next door at the bumping club where the window glass is about to shake loose from the bass.</review>
</record></dataset><record>

< review>
The food is ok-to-good, not great. Service was very good, not excellent, but very good!  Prices are way too high for the products served. Drinks are strong, but then expensive, so it's a wash. This was our 4th visit over several years, and the same each time.  The pupu platter is decent. The southern fried chicken salad is meh. The brisket burger with brie was ordered medium as the kitchen recommends, but came out well. There's supposed to be truffle in there too but tasted like a truffle was only waved over it. Popular with the "in" crowd, so if you care more about being seen...</review>

Incredible atmosphere, wonderful food. On the pricey side, but definitely worth it. I would definitely recommend dining on their patio (unless it's over 100¬∞F out and you can't tolerate that kind of heat). The beautiful trees, lighting and music create a very warm and romantic atmosphere. Great selection of drinks/cocktails, and food, from a sushi menu to deliciously moist and crispy (but not greasy) fried chicken salad, and a perfectly cooked and very tasty skirt steak served with pickled jicama and beets. Everything is made  with much thought. The warm cookie selection for dessert is great! Wonderful restaurant for a romantic dinner or any  celebration.<//text>

< review>
When I visit my girlfriends in Palm Springs we always go here for brunch or happy hour. They have the best brunches, you just can't go wrong. Their food isn't like a Marie Callender's with standard Americanized food. They have more specialty-type food. I love the salads and my girlfriends all the love the cheeseburgers, they are the best around. They have a nice, big bar inside, but we like the outside seating. It's awesome, especially at night. They have lighted trees and the nicest, most comfy patio furniture couches with fire pits. The wait staff is super friendly and always chatting us up. It's fine dining with a casual atmosphere.</review>

<username>Ted Inoue< /username>< time>
1488759426597< /time>
<rate>5< /rate>< review>
A happening scene with great food
Tropicale is one of our favorite places in Palm Springs. The friendly, helpful staff always steers us right when it comes to food suggestions. And if it's your first time, you'll definitely need their recommendations because there are a wide variety of things to try.
If you do the "small plates", keep in mind that these are not small! We always forget and order several and end up with far more food than we expect. You'll probably want to have an entree as your main portion because many of the small plates are fried and you don't want to miss out on the excellent entrees. Just remember to bring your appetite!< /review>

<Response>None</Response><pics>None</pics><Text>Great vibe, excellent service and very good food!
A friend took us here for dinner, as he is a regular and thought we would appreciate it. Well, we loved the decor plus it was live Jazz night and we
were seated in a booth that was just far enough away so that we could hear the jazz and still converse.
Kamden was our server and did a fabulous job of recommending menu items and pacing our meal. He said they were known for their Fried Chicken.....so I decided to take him up on it. Deb had the Diablo Shrimp Caesar and Tony the "Everything Pizza". They both ordered Martini's which came in LARGE Martini glasses and I went with the Hop Nosh IPA. <Rating>5< /Rating>< review>
Just got home from Tropicale.  Great place for happy hour and meeting interesting people.  The drinks are top notch here, and the well brands are much better than what they try to give you at other places.  Great staff too.  We always get one or two of the small plates to snack on (or make a meal out of) during happy hour as well.  And, if you go next door to Copa for one of the shows, you can order Tropicale's small plates there up until 7 PM as well!  Very nice ambiance and always busy.  We haven't gone for a full dinner in a while, but when we do, we will let everyone know how it was!</review>
